Overloading is compile-time polymorphism, while overriding is runtime polymorphism.”

🔹 1. Method Overloading (Compile-Time Polymorphism)
 Definition

Same method name, but:

Different number of parameters OR
Different types of parameters
Example
class Login {
    void login(String username, String password) {
        System.out.println("Login with username/password");
    }

    void login(String token) {
        System.out.println("Login with token");
    }
}
How it works
Resolved at compile time
No inheritance required

 Real-World QA Scenario

In an automation framework:

login("user", "pass");     // UI login
login("api_token");        // API login

You’re using same action (login) but with different inputs

Interview One-Liner

“Overloading improves readability and flexibility by allowing multiple ways to perform the same action.”
