🔹 2. Method Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism)
 Definition
Child class provides specific implementation of a method already defined in parent class
 Example
class BaseTest {
    void setup() {
        System.out.println("Launch browser");
    }
}

class MobileTest extends BaseTest {
    @Override
    void setup() {
        System.out.println("Launch mobile app");
    }
}
How it works
Decided at runtime
Requires inheritance
Real-World QA Scenario
BaseTest test = new MobileTest();
test.setup();

Output:

Launch mobile app
Even though reference is BaseTest
Actual object decides execution → runtime polymorphism
Interview One-Liner

“Overriding enables customization of inherited behavior, which is essential in scalable test frameworks.”

Key Differences
Feature      	                  Overloading	                     Overriding
Polymorphism Type	                Compile-time	                   Runtime
Inheritance	                        Not required	                   Required
Method Signature	                 Must differ	                  Must be same
Decision Time	                     Compile time	                   Runtime
Use Case	                          Flexibility	                 Customization
Real Automation                      Framework                         Comparison

 Example                             click(By locator);
                                   click(WebElement element);
                                    Same action, different inputs

Overriding Example
class BasePage {
    void click() {
        System.out.println("Default click");
    }
}

class LoginPage extends BasePage {
    @Override
    void click() {
        System.out.println("Custom click with wait");
    }
}

Child modifies behavior

TIPS

“In modern automation frameworks, I use overloading for reusable utility methods like login, click, or API calls, while overriding is used in base classes to customize behavior across platforms like web, mobile, or API layers. Overriding also plays a key role in implementing design patterns like Template Method in test frameworks.”

Quick Memory Trick
Overloading = Same name, Different inputs
Overriding = Same method, Different behavior

